## 2026-05-06 — AC5.2 tag: [adopted] not [regression]

**Decision:** AC5.2 (margin icon click opens sidebar and scrolls to comment) tagged `[adopted]`, not `[regression]`.

**Alternatives considered:**
- Tag as `[regression]` — rejected: the user did not explicitly verify this behavior by hand during the interview; the interview only confirmed that the first-comment *fallback* is wrong. The positive hit-test path is a claimed behavior from code inspection, not a hand-verified one.

**Rationale:** Template rule: `[regression]` only for behaviors explicitly verified by hand during interview. All other existing-behavior claims are `[adopted]`.

---

## 2026-05-08 — Frontmatter toggle: unified add/collapse/expand affordance

**Decision:** The frontmatter affordance in `ReadingTextView` is a single toggle button with two states: "Add frontmatter" (when no frontmatter block exists) and "Collapse/Expand frontmatter" (when a frontmatter block exists). The button is always visible; its label and action change based on document state.

**Alternatives considered:**
- Separate "Add frontmatter" button and collapse/expand affordance — rejected: two affordances for the same region creates confusion about which to use.
- Collapse/expand only; no in-app way to add frontmatter — rejected: leaves a dead UI state (button visible but inactive) when no frontmatter exists.
- Only show affordance when frontmatter exists — rejected: means "add frontmatter" has no dedicated UI path.

**Rationale:** Single button, context-sensitive label, no dead states. Folds AC6.1 and the "add frontmatter" case into one coherent interaction. AC6 sub-ACs now cover both the no-frontmatter (add) and has-frontmatter (collapse/expand) paths.

